<p><a name="Trinitarian_background" id="Trinitarian_background"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Christology&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Trinitarian background">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Trinitarian background</span></h2>
<div class="rellink noprint relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Trinity" title="Trinity">Trinity</a></div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Early_Christianity" title="Early Christianity">early Christians</a> first defined exactly how Jesus is related to God the Father in the late first and early second century.<sup id="cite_ref-Rausch2003_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rausch2003-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> However, this definition had taken a long time to formulate. Many of the Christological controversies of the first two centuries of the common era had direct implications for later thinking about how the human and divine are related within the person of Jesus.<sup id="cite_ref-Editors1999_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Editors1999-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table style="text-align:center; float:right; border: 1px solid #aaa; margin: 0 0 1em 1em; background: #f9f9f9; width:17em; padding:0;">
